Here's the full test smell audit for `OrderProcessorTests.cs`:

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smells | Affected Tests |
|----------|--------|----------------|
| 🔴 High | 4 | 4 |
| 🟡 Medium | 5 | 4 |
| 🟢 Low | 1 | class-wide |
| **Total** | **10** | **8 of 9 methods** |

Only `ValidateOrder_NullOrder_ThrowsArgumentNullException` is clean.

---

## 🔴 High Severity

### 1. Conditional Test Logic — `ProcessOrder_SetsCorrectStatus` (line 31)

```csharp
if (result.TotalAmount > 100)
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
else
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
```

One branch is **never tested** — you don't know which. The test always passes regardless of the actual status because one of the two paths will match.

**Fix:** Split into two explicit tests with controlled inputs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_OverHundred_SetsPremiumStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-EXPENSIVE", 2) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
}

[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_UnderHundred_SetsStandardStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-CHEAP", 1) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

---

### 2. Assertion-Free Test — `ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError` (line 43)

```csharp
processor.ProcessOrder(order);
// no assertion
```

This test passes even if `ProcessOrder` returns garbage data, silently corrupts state, or does nothing. The only thing it catches is an unhandled exception.

**Fix:** Assert on the expected outcome:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_SingleItem_ReturnsProcessedResult()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };

    var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);

    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
    Assert.IsTrue(result.TotalAmount > 0);
}
```

---

### 3. Mystery Guest + Resource Optimism — `ImportOrders_FromCsv_ParsesCorrectly` (line 144)

```csharp
var orders = processor.ImportOrders(
    File.ReadAllText(@"C:\TestData\orders.csv"));
```

Depends on a hard-coded Windows file path. This will fail on any machine that doesn't have that exact file, on all Linux/macOS CI agents, and for every new developer. The test reader can't see what the CSV contains, so `5` is also a mystery number.

**Fix:** Inline the test data:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ImportOrders_FromCsv_ParsesCorrectly()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var csv = """
        SKU,Qty
        SKU-1,2
        SKU-2,1
        SKU-3,4
